title: For Sale/Trade:  Mossberg 930 SPX
postcontent: Customized Mossberg 930 SPX -- "Special Purpose eXtreme" 12 gauge tatical shotgun -- great condition.I have probably a couple hundred rounds through this -- about half full-power 00 Buck and half Federal & Remington 7, 7 1/2, and 8-shot target loads.  This shotgun has been *AMAZING* -- it has not suffered A SINGLE MALFUNCTION, not one.  I am from NJ so I had to have this made "NJ'ized" -- this features a custom-made Choate +1 magazine extension tube , making the gun a 6-shot or 5+1 -- however, Choate also made me a custom Heavy Duty magazine spring and their custom heavy duty polymer follower-  because of the configuration and the fact many different shotgun shell types and brands have different lengths, many types of shells actually load 6 in the magazine and one in the chamber, making it a 7-shot.  You can also "ghost load" or add a shell inside the loading latch, making it an 8 shot.  For the record, you can easily purchase a Choate or even Nordic Components +3 magazine extension, making the shotgun a 7+1 or 8 -shot (9 shot with Ghost Loading).I have also purchased and installed the LPA Inc. Fiber  Optic Ghost Ring Sight rear aperture sight to match the front "M16-style" fiber optic post sight.  The rear Ghost Ring aperture features dual green Fiber Optic light pipes to contrast the front red Fiber Optic light pipe , giving you a perfectly awesome Fiber Optic ghost ring sight setup -- front fiber optic tower/post with rear fiber optic ghost ring aperture.  Both are fully adjustable -- the rear being easily adjustable with just the rim of a shotgun shell.I have also installed a precision-fit LimbSaver recoil pad which amazingly reduces the recoil -- it made a huge difference.  I also rigged up a sling and added a soft stock shell-carrier for a few extra rounds.This shotgun is in great condition -- the absolutely only issue is the fact that the finish isn't pristine, you can clearly see in the pictures there a couple-a-few scuffs.  This is only because of the fact Mossberg uses an aluminum receiver with steel parts, and the bluing/oxidizing process they use for finishing is weak at best.  Choate uses a different bluing entirely , which you can see because the mag ext. is different shade of black than the rest.  The gun is pristine, has been treated perfectly, was my baby for a long time -- but i have a collection of shotguns, I want to buy a 1911, so I'm going to let this go.... It's an amazing shotgun.  In early 2010, the Mossberg 930 SPX was the hottest firearm on the market, people were buying them and then immediately asking $1,200-$1,300 online.Ok thanks , hope to hear from someone who will love this bad mama jama like I did.$650 or best trade/offer
